history from the Punic times to the eve of the Islamic conquest. She demonstrates that during the period when Christianity was spreading to both city and countryside in North Africa, a convergence of economic interests narrowed the gap between the rustici and the urbani, creating a consumer revolution of sorts among the peasants. This book's postcolonial perspective points to the empowerment of the North African peasants and gives voice to lower social classes across the Roman world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aConsumption (Economics)xSocial aspects. 0aDonatists. 0aPreachingxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aRoman provincesxAdministration. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aarchaeological.  achristian north africa.  achristianity.  aclass differences.  aconsumer revolution.  acultural history.  aeconomic interests.  ahistorical.  ahistory buffs.  aimperialism.  aislamic conquest.  alower classes.  anonfiction.  anorth africa.  apeasant society.  apeasants.  apolitical.  apostcolonial perspective.  aprovincial peasants.  apunic times.  aregional history.  areligious history.  aroman population.  aroman world.  arustici.  asocial classes.  asocial history.  aspread of christianity.  aurbani.  avillage settings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025439840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094777140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947771/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY